		<div class="post" id="post-3636541">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,3636541)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-3636541">
																		I like what the story is trying to say but not the manner in which it is saying it.
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/soullesssingularity" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(637830); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=637830&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227397" alt="SoullessSingularity" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=637830)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/soullesssingularity" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(637830); return false;" >SoullessSingularity</a></span> <span class="odate time_1511208297 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">20 Nov 2017 20:04</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3636541">
									

<p>I downvoted because the second-person doesn't work for me. In particular, second person works in immersing a given reader in their environment- forcing them to feel more intimate with the story itself. However, I've found in this piece it lacks pretty much everything else that such a story that demands intimacy with the reader has. It has no grounding. It doesn't engage any senses other than sight. What senses are used beyond sight are so wrapped in metaphor that I have no idea the actual sensory input, it just becomes the abstract idea of a sensory input, and thus draws me further from the piece.</p>
<p>Because the entire story is written in this manner, I cannot fully engage with the piece- every time the story referred to me as &quot;you&quot;, I cannot actually feel like I am there. The pacing and the imagery is good, but I'm confused as to the relationship between the reader and the story, given simultaneously the second person and the lack of actual grounding technique.</p>
<p>EDIT: If the point is that there is no sensory input other than sight, then perhaps there should be some allusion as to its lacking- some significant stuff happens here, violent, painful, and the protagonist does not even notice its pain or its lack of pain. Similarly, loudness or its lack of loudness.</p>
<p>If one wanted to avoid using other sensory input I ould recommend other things- stories like this usually work better with a sense of normalcy beforehand- a way for the reader to understand where they are so that the story can then drag the rug from underneath them for a more effective immersion into the unreal. Think of, for example, Portal 2's opening- it gave you a sense of being in a room before showing you you're in a small chamber precariously atop a pile of chambers in an unfathomably massive room full of them. A similar sense I think may be effective in grounding a reader in a sense of who &quot;you&quot; are, and where &quot;you&quot; are, before throwing all of that out the window.</p>

							</div>

										<div class="signature">
					<hr class="signature-separator"/>
					

<p>Living the dream, or dreaming the life?</p>

				</div>
					
